<span class=title>   Re: Project pegasus.</span><hr size=1> To launch from Earth requires a high thrust to weight ratio, and that excludes many fo the propulsion systems that *might* be able to give you the fuel efficency you would need for such an ambitious plan. You would probibly need to use a nuclear pulse drive, either fission or fusion. Your best bet is probably a fusion pulse drive like ICAN, which is basicly a fusion Orion. Fusion provides about 3 times the energy per unit mass as fission. Even then you are talking 10000+ tons to accomplish what you want. A space launched ICAN-style ship is about 5000 tons, ground launching all that, with reinforcements for launch, would take a ton of propellant. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=460.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Project pegasus.</span><hr size=1> I fiqured you guys would go with a Orion system (thats why I said &quot;if Orion system in used, assume that fusion warheads will be used&quot;). But remember, this ship after dropping off the astronauts would explore some of the outer planets, launch probe's, ect, then return to mars, pick them up, and return to earth. <br>
